{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"3b4f31b8-85e0-4ac1-86c7-e66432b3ab94","content":"On macOS, the OS automatically generates crash reports — no `createdump` needed.\n\n**Crash reports (`.ips` files):**\n```\n~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n```\nLook for files matching your process name. These contain the native backtrace, signal info, and register state.\n\n**Core dumps** (disabled by default — enable before reproducing):\n```bash\nsudo mkdir -p /cores\nsudo chmod 1777 /cores\nulimit -c unlimited\n./your-app  # reproduce the crash\nls /cores/   # core.<pid> appears here\n```\n\n**Quick access:** Open **Console.app → Crash Reports** to browse `.ips` files with a GUI.\n\nThe `.ips` crash report is usually sufficient for initial triage of NativeAOT crashes since it includes the full native stack trace.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"29d060dd-81c7-4fe5-b912-84b2b140c437","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about finding crash dumps/reports for a NativeAOT .NET app on macOS, specifically when `createdump` isn't available. This is a diagnostic/knowledge question — I don't need to search a codebase. Let me provide a concise answer.\n\nOn macOS, when an app crashes, the system automatically generates crash reports (`.ips` files). For NativeAOT apps where `createdump` isn't available, the user should look at:\n\n1. **macOS crash reports** — stored in `~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/` (or `/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/` for system-wide). These are `.ips` files.\n\n\n2. **Core dumps** — macOS disables core dumps by default, but they can be enabled with `ulimit -c unlimited`, which will write them to the `/cores/` directory.\n\nLet me give a concise answer.","outputTokens":439,"requestId":"2040:29D6CF:71B10C:845317:69F011D9"},"id":"dcf0ffdf-9264-4938-a7de-5b8b4fece575","timestamp":"2026-04-28T01:48:19.950Z","parentId":"82af9f43-7ceb-49e2-b10c-3da8b1ed1092"}
